claim.claim-text:
1. A spring action shovel comprising:
a hand grip, a shaft, a shock absorbing mechanism, and a shovel blade;
wherein the spring action shovel is a hand-operated tool for moving material;
wherein the spring action shovel is adapted to be held by placing a first user hand on the shaft and a second user hand on the hand grip;
wherein the shock absorbing mechanism is located within the shaft and is configured to minimize injuries due to repetitive or impactful motions of the shovel blade;
wherein the shock absorbing mechanism comprises a stiffness adjustment that is adapted for a user to vary the compressive stiffness of the shock absorbing mechanism.

2. The spring action shovel according to claim 1
wherein the hand grip is adapted to be grasped by the user;
wherein the hand grip is a D-grip comprising a straight horizontal top portion and a semi-circular or V-shaped lower portion;
wherein the hand grip is coupled to the upper end of the shaft.

3. The spring action shovel according to claim 2
wherein the top of the shaft is coupled to the hand grip and the bottom of the shaft is coupled to the shovel blade;
wherein the shaft comprises an outer shaft at the top and an inner shaft at the bottom.

4. The spring action shovel according to claim 3
wherein the inner shaft has a smaller diameter that the outer shaft and slides within the outer shaft;
wherein the length of the shaft is variable.

5. The spring action shovel according to claim 4
wherein the top end of the outer shaft is terminated by an upper plug;
wherein the bottom end of the inner shaft is terminated by a lower plug.

6. The spring action shovel according to claim 5
wherein the outer shaft is a cylindrical tube comprising an upper cavity;
wherein the upper cavity is a hollow central portion of the outer shaft;
wherein the top of the outer shaft is coupled to the bottom of the hand grip.

7. The spring action shovel according to claim 6
wherein the inner shaft is a cylindrical tube comprising a lower cavity;
wherein the lower cavity is a hollow central portion of the inner shaft;
wherein the bottom of the inner shaft is coupled to the shovel blade using a shovel attachment screw.

8. The spring action shovel according to claim 7
wherein the outside diameter of inner shaft is less than the inside diameter of outer shaft such that the inner shaft slides into the upper cavity;
wherein the upper cavity provides space for the inner shaft to slide further into the outer shaft to accommodate compression of a spring;
wherein the upper cavity and the lower cavity provide space to house the spring.

10. The spring action shovel according to claim 8
wherein the shock absorbing mechanism is a device that absorbs and dampens shock impulses;
wherein the shock absorbing mechanism comprises the spring and the stiffness adjustment;
wherein the spring is housed within the shaft where the spring is inaccessible for safety reasons.

14. The spring action shovel according to claim 13
wherein the spring enables the inner shaft to move relative to the outer shaft;
wherein the longitudinal axes of the outer shaft, the inner shaft, and the spring are aligned along the longitudinal axis of the shaft.

15. The spring action shovel according to claim 14
wherein the spring is a helical compression spring;
wherein the spring comprises an upper spring, a lower spring, and a buffer bushing;
wherein the upper spring is located above the lower spring;
wherein the upper spring is coupled to the lower spring at the buffer bushing;
wherein the top end of the upper spring is coupled to the bottom of a spring block.

16. The spring action shovel according to claim 15
wherein the stiffness adjustment is adapted for the user to grasp and turn in order to adjust compression of the spring;
wherein the stiffness adjustment comprises a spring adjustment knob, a spring adjustment rod, a guide screw, and the spring block;
wherein the spring adjustment knob is accessible within the fork of the hand grip;
wherein the spring adjustment knob is coupled to the top of the spring adjustment rod such that turning the spring adjustment knob rotates the spring adjustment rod.

17. The spring action shovel according to claim 16
wherein the bottom end of the spring adjustment rod is threaded and threadedly couples to an aperture in the top center of the spring block;
wherein rotation of the spring adjustment rod moves the spring block linearly within the shaft;
wherein the spring block moves up within the shaft when the spring adjustment knob is turned in a first rotational direction and the spring block moves down within the shaft when the spring adjustment knob is turned in a second rotational direction, or vice versa;
wherein turning the spring adjustment knob changes the length, and therefore the amount of compression, of the spring.

20. The spring action shovel according to claim 19
wherein the guide screw is coupled to the outer shaft and passes laterally through the center of the outer shaft;
wherein the guide screw passes through an adjustment slot in the spring block;
wherein the guide screw permits the spring block to move linearly within the shaft and prevents the spring block from rotating within the shaft.

1. A non-transitory computer-readable medium with a computer program stored thereon for controlling a tillage implement, wherein when executed by one or more processors the computer program instructs the one or more processors to perform the following steps:
receive a first target value and a second target value from a user, wherein each of the first target value and the second target value is a target soil condition value;
receive a priority for each of the first target value and the second target value;
obtain, via one or more sensors, information indicative of a first soil condition value and a second soil condition value;
generate the first soil condition value and the second soil condition value based on the information indicative of the first soil condition value and the second soil condition value;
compare the first soil condition value and the second soil condition value with the first target value and the second target value, respectively;
adjust operation of the tillage implement based on the comparison of the first soil condition value and the second soil condition value with the first target value and the second target value, respectively; and
prioritize operation of the tillage implement based on the priority.

17. An agricultural system comprising:
a tillage implement including at least one ground-engaging tool;
one or more sensor configured to obtain information indicative of soil condition values; and
a controller comprising a processing element and a memory element, wherein the controller is configured to:
receive a first target value and a second target value from a user, wherein each of the first target value and the second target value is a target soil condition value;
receive a priority for each of the first target value and the second target value;
obtain, via the one or more sensors, information indicative of a first soil condition value and a second soil condition value;
generate the first soil condition value and the second soil condition value based on the information indicative of the first soil condition value and the second soil condition value;
compare the first soil condition value and the second soil condition value with the first target value and the second target value, respectively;
adjust operation of the tillage implement based on the comparison of the first soil condition value and the second soil condition value with the first target value and the second target value, respectively; and
prioritize operation of the tillage implement based on the priority.

18. A non-transitory computer-readable medium with a computer program stored thereon for controlling a tillage implement, wherein when executed by one or more processors the computer program instructs the one or more processors to perform the following steps:
operate the tillage implement based on an original target value, wherein the original target value comprises a target soil condition value;
manually receive, via a user interface, an adjustment to an operating parameter of the tillage implement;
obtain, via one or more sensors, information indicative of a soil condition value after the tillage implement operates using the adjustment to the operating parameter of the tillage implement;
generate the soil condition value based on the information indicative of the soil condition value;
generate a new target value based on the generated soil condition value; and
operate the tillage implement based on the new target value.
